    "created_at": "2014-08-06T00:06:29Z",
    "updated_at": "2014-08-06T00:06:29Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Come to think of it, the `expanding_mean(..., center=True)` results look just plain odd, notwithstanding the final `NaN`s. There's no way in !$# that anyone would want that. I understand why they are the way they are: `expanding_*(arg, ...)` is calculated as `rolling_*(arg, ..., window=len(arg), min_periods=0)`, so everything is shifted by a _fixed_ `(len(arg)-1)/2`. I suppose the \"right\" thing to do is to \"halve\" the indices, rather than shift them, but  it still seems sort of odd.\n\nPerhaps best simply to remove the `center` argument from all the `expanding_*` functions? (I'm not sure it's that easy, the way the code is written, but ignore that for now.) Given the odd behavior, I very much doubt anyone is using them with `center=True`.\n"
  },
